<div>Hi Rajat</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div>This is how I understand they get 64tb.</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div>It comes more from the seg. unit than paging unit.</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div>there are 13 seg registers..</div>
<div>each seg has 32 bit offset</div>
<div>and can be from gdt or ldt..</div>
<div>thus total space is2^(32&#43;13&#43;2)=3D64tb.</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div>http://stackoverflow.com/questions/5444984/64-terabytes-of-virtual-mem=
ory-how</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div>if you connect this to what we did in class&nbsp;</div>
<div>we actually have 4 segments ... kernel code and data</div>
<div>and user code and data. so speaking in the same language we are actual=
ly working with 16gb of virtual memory space.</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div>However the addressable space is just 4gb ie 2^32. ie. all the 16gb ge=
t mapped to the same 4gb of addressable space. This is what we are working =
with and splitting into kernel space and user space.</div>
<div><br>
</div>
